has affected not just the general economy (doubling our national debt in just four years), and businesses (NBC reporting that businesses are turning to the 30 hour week as the &quot;new norm&quot; to avoid not going out of business due to costs of Obama Care), but even (maybe especially) schools.  Students in Latvia, Chile, and Brazil are making academic gains three times faster than American students.  It isn't unfair to say that our educational system of being &quot;kinder, gentler&quot; has also made our students dumber.  Take the red pill America, or take the blue pill.  The colors represent the pop culture symbols of  blissful illusion (blue) or embracing the painful truth of reality (red).  Private schools the world over have gone the distance to give a child a higher level of remedial skills, and higher science and math skills that public schools have been unwilling to address.  Private schools traditionally do not offer everything the public system does (ie they won't have the chess or glee clubs...) but they churn out a strong academic student with a higher degree of college entrance and graduation rate.  Poor Allison Benedikt may not have been able to attend a private school, and it may be the cause of her not being able to properly spell her last name. Alas, the rest of us attending the public school she went to may not (in the end) help any of us. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1659" language="en" documentId="2518" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="smsrt" date="Aug 29, 2013 9:03PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="2518" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1659"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>